description:
src/lib.rs:284 'resp.bytes().await' reads the entire response body into memory unbounded. GCP Secret Manager's documented max payload is 64 KiB, but a misbehaving or compromised endpoint (DNS hijack, TLS-MITM if cert pinning is absent) could return arbitrarily large data.

Defense-in-depth: cap the response size. reqwest exposes Response::content_length() (advisory) and the easiest enforcement is a tower::limit::RequestBodyLimitLayer or an explicit chunked read with a counter. A simple approach:
  let mut buf = Vec::with_capacity(4096);
  let mut stream = resp.bytes_stream();
  while let Some(chunk) = stream.next().await { buf.extend_from_slice(&chunk?); if buf.len() > MAX_BODY { return Err(...); } }

Alternatively, set Content-Length sanity check before consuming.

Low priority because the realistic threat (TLS broken) implies a bigger problem, but a 1 GB response from a compromised endpoint would OOM the process before TLS detection.

Cross-crate aspect: same gap exists in all REST backends in the workspace.
